segments.text: And so we did that.
We spent about $500 on high-grade lumber and set up the first loft in Moore Hall, and consequently became tour guides to a lot of people from around campus who wanted to see our construction.
So we kind of customized it.
Right.
And what else?
Television?
Had a television, yes.
Had a television, had a stereo.
You had to have a stereo.
I would have to say that in 1976 a stereo was much more highly regarded than a television.
It seemed like you could go somewhere and watch TV, but you couldn't go just anywhere and listen to the music you wanted to listen to.
And did you have any place to cook and refrigerate?
Cooking was not allowed.
We did have a refrigerator.
In fact, everybody had a refrigerator.
We rented those for $50 a semester.
We in fact had two at one time, which I think was a violation of dorm policy.

but nonetheless we did have two because we needed a place to store all the fajitas I was bringing back from Laredo and tortillas and things like that that I subsequently was giving away and then my father said you know you may want to curtail that a little bit because
$50 every time you come home for fajitas is getting out of hand.
But interestingly enough, I had people offer me two and $2.50 a pound for these fajitas that they couldn't buy in College Station.
And they'd also offer me a little more if I'd cook them for them.
Yeah, we had two refrigerators and a little warming plate, which I think again was illegal.
The main thing you saw in dorms were popcorn poppers and refrigerators, and that was about it.
Were there telephones in every room then?
There were telephones in every room, sure were, and they were all rotary dial.
There wasn't anything as a push button at that time.
Before I left A&M, the push button was introduced.
In the average room in those days, what kind of beverages were refrigerated in the rooms?
Festive beverages, I would categorize them as.
That is another little anecdote of my Laredo upbringing.

After the fall of 76 trip to Laredo where about eight of my buddies in the dorm accompanied me on a deer hunt, we went to the Cadillac bar and you've got to understand how popular an 18-year-old, and the legal drinking age at that time was 18,
but how popular an 18-year-old can be when your father is the owner of the Cadillac bar in Nuevo Laredo, Mexico.
We had to limit the trip to eight, and deer hunting was not the draw.
But after that trip, well, during that trip, I introduced those seven other buddies of mine to some Mexican beer, Bohemia, Carta Blanca, Corona.
And they found out that we could buy a case of that for as little as $3.70.
And I think we brought back 16 cases of beer.
So yes, at that time, we did have some beer in our refrigerators.
As far as you know, in those years, how often did a student get drunk in the dormitory?
Haskell, I never got drunk in the dormitory, but I did
see one person who was, as I would categorize it, really out of control drunk in my history at A&M, and that was it.
I never saw just a whole lot of drunken
Aggies in our dorm.
And in that era, did Aggies normally drink beer or did they drink whiskey and other?
Beer.
Beer.
Beer.
While we're on that topic, what were the most popular student hangouts for beer in those days?
The Dixie Chicken was only two years old.
when I got to A&M, and it didn't enjoy the notoriety that it does today, but the proximity was such that you could walk to the chicken from Moore Hall in the span of about four minutes.
So it was the premier spot for us.
There was a place called the Sports Club that went out of business while I was at A&M.
that was quite popular, particularly with athletes.
It was more of a discotheque at that time.
The Hall of Fame was a Thursday or Friday night regular, and that was because you had the opportunity to dance there that you didn't have at the Dixie Chicken.
What about Sparky's?
Was it good?
was really unknown to me during my years at A&M.
And the only time I really knew much about it was when some friends of mine who were in the corps told me to meet them at Sparky's.
And I did, but it was predominantly a corps hangout.
When you and your buddies went off campus, did you ever encounter any difficulties of civilian and corps members off campus?
None whatsoever.
Never saw it.
In all my experiences, whether it was the
a student experience like bonfire or an academic experience like studying together or just student leadership.
I never saw that animosity or anything like that.
What about the, using the politically correct word, diversity?
How diverse was the student body and how were minority student body individuals treated?
I would have to
categorize this as more of an international student versus minorities, domestic minorities, if you will.

I have one recollection of a very sad experience that I witnessed in the registration process over at Heaton Hall, where an international student was having difficulty registering, and the young, not the young, but the woman behind the desk, instead of maybe just listening a little more attentively, spoke louder as if he didn't understand,
and his hearing was perfectly fine, and ultimately just kind of
treated him in a very degrading way and shuffled him off and I took that opportunity to visit with that person.
It was very disappointing.
He was from Panama and since I spoke Spanish it was an easy conversation for me to have and helped him out and to this day I still keep in touch with him.
But as far as minorities go, my background was such that I was a minority.
And all of a sudden, when I came to A&M, I had never seen as many blonde-haired, blue-eyed girls in my whole life.
And that's why I quickly fell out of love in 1975.
I would have to categorize A&M as a very inclusive atmosphere.
I just didn't see any real challenge to a multicultural problem.
I think that's true.
I've always said the key thing, are you an Aggie?
Come on, if you're an Aggie, let's go.
That's right.
If you're not and don't like it, well fine, hit the road.
No, I enjoyed, I was invited to play in what was then known as the Pan American Games, which I guess historically had been four
Central American countries, and it was nothing more than a softball tournament, a swimming volleyball weekend, golf, basketball I think was introduced at one point, soccer.
But one of the real highlights of my time at A&M was every spring playing in the Pan American games and being invited to do so just because I was from Laredo, spoke Spanish,
and appreciated their culture.
And that meant something to me.
Okay, please, I'm reading my notes now, please recall some of the jokes, pranks, or other good bull that you may have known about during your years at A&M, whether you were involved or not.
Okay.
Well, I'll just be very honest with you.
By default, once again, in living in that corner room, by happenstance, also found out that the key to my room was known as a passkey.
This was brought to my attention by a fellow who I had lent my key to to get into my dorm and found out that it opened his room just by default once again.
And so we tried it on a few other doors and found out it opened every room in the dorm, including the dorm, the basement door.
where we found a cache of fireworks in the fall of 1976.
And this made me quite popular with some of my buddies when we needed access to those fireworks or other items that had been sequestered down there.

But in the spring of 1977, this all came to a crashing end when a fellow named Willie Gaines, class of 1979, who is now a very prominent doctor here in College Station, was the fourth floor RA, and early in the morning,

He came walking down the first floor hall and heard something and took his own passkey, opened up that basement door, went down the little steps, and found me and two of my buddies neatly wrapping up in a pillowcase fireworks and some other things that had been confiscated.
And he was very polite but very firm and said,
How did y'all get down here?
And I finally had to fess up.
Well, that was the end of my passkey days.

But the results of some of that over a six, seven month period were bottle rockets across the quad, fireworks at two in the morning, fireworks under doors, fireworks in the air conditioning and heating vents.
And I was a part of that, I must admit.
One of the real ugly things I think that took place, turned out to be ugly anyway, was we had a head resident on our floor that just wasn't in tune with the rest of the dorm.

I was literally talked into this prank, and we were out in the country, and we found a goat, and we thought it would be a neat thing if we turned that goat loose in this fellow's dorm room while he was gone for the weekend.
Our thoughts were that the goat would just maybe defecate in some strategic locations, and that would be it.
We didn't realize that that goat would not only defecate and urinate but proceed to eat
everything it could find within its reach, whether it was wood, metal, paper, toothpaste, cologne, you name it.
And so the byproduct of that, pardon the pun, was some of his refuse was quite aromatic and quite inconsistent with that of a normal goat out in the pasture.
And it just added to the...
It was just hard to believe.
We thought our head resident was gone on Friday, coming home on Saturday.
He had actually left Friday afternoon and wasn't coming home till early, early Sunday morning.
So while we thought he would find the goat midday Saturday, he didn't find the goat until mid-morning Sunday.
And it is quite amazing, Haskell, what a mature goat can do in the span of about 60 hours to an eight by 10 dorm room.
Did any students get punished for that?
Yes, I did.
I did.
In fact, I was brought before the, I think his name was Rick Crow.
I think he's still here.
And I had to go see him and justify why I had done that.
And there were some weekends that I had to sit and do some service around the dorm, which I did, and my buddies had to do as well.
And I paid the price.
What about, were there drown-outs in civilian dorms?
Oh, yes.
Oh, gosh, yes.
crap outs, whatever you want to call them.

I won't give you the definitive term, but what you basically did was take whatever trash can was in the hall, usually a 40 gallon, 35 gallon plastic, big tub trash can, and regardless of what was in it,
And sometimes it wasn't what you might expect, but fill it up with water and appropriately lean it on somebody's door and then knock vigorously and run like hell.
And that was quite popular.
Did you ever get drowned out?
I never got drowned out, believe it or not.
I did not.
I had some shaving cream come flying into my room out of an album cover one evening.
I had a flaming bag of refuse left on my door one time, but other than that, no, I didn't have the drown out.
And nobody played any games with anybody's cars?
Never.
Never?
Okay.
What about when somebody was down the hall showering?
Any things in the showers?
Yeah.
I don't have real vivid recollections of that, but the one that I do have, I don't know that it's appropriate to put on record, but it had to do with a fellow who had
had too many festive beverages one night.
And his roommate, of all people, led this charge because he was tired of his roommate, I think, coming in drunk at 3 and 4 in the morning.
And this young man who was hungover on a Sunday morning
was sitting in an open stall, which we had probably seven in this community bath set up in Moore Hall, and they were going to drown him out.
But before they could drown him out, he caught wind of what was going to happen, and this is a true story, as ugly as it is, and believe it or not, reached into the toilet bowl and grabbed
turd and flung it and hit his roommate in the head with this thing and his roommate slips on the way out trying to get away from this deal and cuts himself right across the eye.
So he's running down the hall on a Sunday morning and I'm coming this way and here he is with
with feces on his forehead and blood all over his eyes.
And I can't tell you what thoughts went through my mind thinking, what has this guy done?
What about in the dining hall?
Were there games played, tricks played during that time?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
Yeah, it was very popular to confuse things such as
I'm trying to think, but you'd often want to mix salt instead of sugar with somebody's iced tea.
and things like that.
Were you and your buddies, did anybody ever go down into the steam tunnels?
Oh, yes.
Yeah, I did that.
That was very popular.
Describe, as far as you know, the extent of the steam tunnels.
They were rather accommodating in 1976.
I was led by a group who actually didn't live in Moore Hall but lived in
in Crocker Hall and lived in Davis Gary Hall.
And I think the goal was that we wanted a retreat from an attack that they had planned
on the south side dormitories when we were going to have a water fight, which we did with Aston and Dunn Halls.
And rather than running back through campus, it was thought that we would just disappear on the south side and reappear on the north side.
And believe it or not, those steam tunnels accommodated even the tallest member of our party, which was Willie Gaines, of all people, and he's about 6'5".
Steam tunnels were quite extensive around the campus.
Were you aware when you were an undergraduate of the existence of any secret fraternities?
No, sir.
None.
Was not made aware of any until I took this job in 1981 and had some people refer to the Sticks, and I can't remember.
True Texans.
That was the first I'd heard of it, and that was 1982.
Let's see.
Back to class.
What were the
What were the normal guidelines to class attendance and behavior that you understood?
I don't mean that somebody wrote them down, huh?
Well, it was just different for different classes, Haskell.
There were some classes where the professor or the teaching assistant or the graduate assistant, as it were, demanded and just penalized you for not attending class.
There were others where, like in Judge Stewart's class, you knew intuitively if you didn't attend that there was going to be a problem because you could read that whole book
and not pass the test.
And so it was just different for different professors.
There was a lot of class cutting though in those days, and I'm sure there still is.
But it surprised me that people could blow off, and that was the terminology then, could blow off a class as readily as they could.
And survive.
All right.
What about in class?
What about any pranks or tricks in class?
Oh, I'm sure there were some.
You know, I'd have to think about it.
There's none that just come to mind.
right away.

I did see a professor, a full professor, throw an eraser at a member of the Corps who had fallen asleep in his class, and I thought that was funny, but it turned out to be a bad situation for the professor.
The MSC, what role did it play in campus life?
At that time, it was the hub of most of the campus activity between
8 a.m. and 6 p.m.
It really was where you gathered either to drink coffee, study, visit.
It was the bookstore, so to speak, for anybody that lived on campus, whether that was just the purchase of a t-shirt or, in fact, a textbook or a...
I'm trying to think what they called them now.
You may remember being a professor yourself.
Was it a Scantron sheet?
I think so.
Yeah, that's where you had to go to get that.
So it wasn't the extensive
building that it is now, but it was a very comfortable place to go and drink coffee or drink a Coke or meet somebody or study.
Did you get acquainted with the director of the MSC during your shooting years?
No, sir, did not.
I knew who he was.
It was Wayne Stark.
I had some friends in the College of Business that were quite enamored with his networking.
Now, the YMCA wasn't much.
No, sir, not really.
In fact, that was where the vice president for student activities was located, Dr. John Coldis.
And I didn't have to see him, but that is where I went to see Rick Crowe, who I mentioned a minute ago.
Guyon Hall was leveled at about that time.
Prior to my getting to A&M, Guyon Hall was leveled, yes.
This will not be part of the finished product, but one of the real goofs that A&M made was that the guy and family was not notified in advance.
And the first they knew about it was a picture they saw in the Waco paper of the rubble.
And a couple years later they gave Baylor a very impressive gift, I think three or four million dollars.
And think how handsome those columns at the south end of Military Walk would have been if in future planning those columns had been left to be a part of the Rudder Center
you know, a kind of a part of the tradition.
I've heard great stories about Guy and Hall, and I wished it would have been around when I got here.
Let's see.
Let's go back to it.
As far as you recall, what did a semester or a year cost, and where did that money come from?
I was indeed blessed that my father provided 100% of my college expenses.
I didn't work while I was at A&M, and that was a real fortunate situation.
Looking back on it, I think I wished
I would have worked.
There's two big regrets I probably have at A&M.
One, interestingly, is that I was not in the Corps.
I think I would have been an excellent cadet.
I witnessed subsequently a lot of the camaraderie that
members of the Corps have enjoyed over their lives.

But my second biggest regret is that I didn't work when I was a student and that didn't provide me an opportunity to get to know more of the inner workings of A&M and discipline myself to a more regimented study schedule.
But I'd say that the typical semester at A&M was about $1,500 to $2,000.
It was a rather inexpensive
I'm trying to make sure I've got books in that.
Tuition was, I want to say, $4 a semester hour.
I think that's right.
I want to say room and board was $643.
Rather inexpensive.
used books, three to four hundred dollars at the most, including varying materials that went with that, such as lab materials and so on.
But overall, I know I got by for less than two thousand dollars a semester.
Describe the student body in terms of
what were their basic attitudes about life, and what family background, income, and small town or big city or what?
Describe that.
I'd say small towns more than big cities.
Knew a lot of kids from Houston just by percentages, but met a lot of kids from
places like San Angelo, Tyler, Beaumont, Lake Jackson, Pearsall.
I'd have to say that most of the kids at least that I chose to run around with were very conservative in their backgrounds and were raised
with somewhat of an agricultural background.
And it was interesting that here I was in the College of Business, but running around with a lot of ag majors.
And I think it was because of my rural interest and background, but didn't see a lot of idealism.
At least I didn't witness it.
Now, maybe it's because we didn't have much of a College of Liberal Arts, but mostly a strong presence of
disciplined and regimented engineers and ag majors and good old boys type.
Didn't see many you know earrings or tattoos or long hair or any radical dress really.
And in terms of
Religious faith, were you aware of any Jewish kids?
One.
One is all I knew.
Did it matter?
No.
He was the only real Jewish student that I knew well.
I'm sure I know there were others.
Were there any religious activities on campus in those days that you remember?
No.
I can remember the Baptist Student Union being very aggressive in their recruitment of our dorm.
I was a Catholic.
I was involved in St. Mary's Church.
I say I was involved.
I attended.
I don't know that I was involved.
I played on a softball team.
Describe, as far as you recall, the St. Mary's activities relating to the campus then.
St. Mary's was aggressive as well in making themselves known as the Catholic Church for students, both in their proximity and in their attitude and, quite frankly, their scheduling.
on behalf of students.
Their first Sunday service, I think, was 845, and I assume the rationale for that was that students didn't roll out of bed too early on Sundays.
But they also had a
Oh, I forget what they called it.
It was a mass where kids played guitars and drums and involved music.
Was there a priest assigned to the campus?
No, not to my recollection.
Not to my recollection.
Were there any weeknight activities at St. Mary's?
Yes there were, several, several.
And I attended some and I'd have to say that between the Baptist church and the Catholic church, those were the two dominant religious cultures that I saw.
the major optional student activity organizations, band and so forth, what were the, in terms of prestige, what were the big prestigious student organizations?
Believe it or not, I think RHA, because of

in it it was parents weekend and they always put on casino night and that was quite a prestigious committee to serve on interestingly enough i didn't see or know of a lot of kids who were serving on the muster committee the campus muster committee
where now that probably is the most prestigious committee there is.
Student government, obviously, student senate and so on, very prestigious and very sought after.
But RHA involved so much fun that there was quite a desire to be involved with the Residence Hall Association.
And who were some of the key student leaders during your undergraduate years?
Oh, Johnny Lane.
Bobby Tucker, who's now back here on campus.
Randy Mays, who I had a crush on when I was in school.
Jeff Hancock was our head Yale leader.
Joe Wright.
Tim McManus.
And the president of the student body was a?
Bobby Tucker.
Bobby Tucker.
What about some of the other years?
Bob Harvey, who I've come to get to know here just recently in his service on the Texas A&M Foundation trustees.
Bob was a well-respected member of the Corps of Cadets and was a fine student body president, and I thought was a guy that I always looked up to.
Fred McClure had just finished his role as student body president when I got here.
Oh, I'm sorry.
I thought that it would have been.
Okay, because I was waiting for it.
So he had just finished.
He had just finished, yeah.
What did you and your civilian buddies think about the Aggie band and the singing cadets?
Took great pride in it.
Took great pride in the band and the singing cadets as well.
My second roommate at A&M was a member of the scene cadets, and I had great insight into what they represented on behalf of A&M.
So, yeah, I had a tremendous appreciation and respect for the scene cadets.
Great ambassadors for Texas A&M.
I saw a new, to me, a new bumper sticker the other day.
A young lady driving a car with a bumper sticker saying, I love my BQ.
Yeah, I've seen that before.
I hadn't seen that one.
Do you remember some important celebrity person?
